Advantages
	• High prediction accuracy. 
	• Reduces overfitting by combining multiple trees. 
	• Works well with both numerical and categorical data. 
	• Can handle large datasets efficiently. 
	• Robust to noise and missing values. 
	• Provides feature importance for model interpretation. 

Disadvantages
	• Training is slower than a single Decision Tree. 
	• Requires more memory. 
	• Difficult to interpret because it contains many trees. 
	• Computationally expensive for very large forests. 

Applications
	• Medical diagnosis 
	• Fraud detection 
	• Credit scoring 
	• Loan approval 
	• Customer churn prediction 
	• Recommendation systems 
	• Stock market analysis 
	• Image classification 
	• Weather forecasting

Working of Random Forest
Random Forest works through the following steps:
Step 1: Collect the Dataset
The algorithm begins with a labeled training dataset.
Example:
Age	Income	Loan Approved
25	30000	No
35	60000	Yes
40	80000	Yes

Step 2: Bootstrap Sampling
Random Forest creates several random datasets by selecting samples with replacement from the original dataset. This process is called Bootstrap Sampling.
Example:
Original Dataset:
A B C D E
Sample 1:
A C C D E
Sample 2:
B B C D A
Each sample is slightly different.

Step 3: Random Feature Selection
Instead of using all features, Random Forest randomly selects a subset of features for each decision tree.
Example
Features:
	• Age 
	• Income 
	• Education 
	• Experience 
Tree 1 may use:
	• Age 
	• Income 
Tree 2 may use:
	• Income 
	• Experience 
Tree 3 may use:
	• Age 
	• Education 
This randomness increases diversity among the trees.

Step 4: Build Multiple Decision Trees
Each bootstrap sample is used to train one Decision Tree.

Dataset
│
 ├── Tree 1
 ├── Tree 2
 ├── Tree 3
 ├── Tree 4
  └── Tree 5

Step 5: Prediction
For a new observation, every tree predicts an output.
Example
Tree	Prediction
Tree 1	Approved
Tree 2	Approved
Tree 3	Rejected
Tree 4	Approved
Tree 5	Approved

Step 6: Final Decision
